{"title_page": "Nikki Finke", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Nikki Finke\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Nikki Finke<ref name=\"nytengage\">Staff report (October 20, 1974). [https://www.nytimes.com/1974/10/20/archives/law-student-fiance-of-nikki-finke.html Law Student Fiance of Nikki Finke.] ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref>\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1953|12}}\n| birth_place   = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| occupation    = [[Writer]], [[journalist]], [[blog]]ger, [[publisher]]\n| spouse=[[Jeffrey W. Greenberg]] (1980\u20131982)\n}}\n\n'''Nikki Finke''' (born 1953) is an American [[blog]]ger, [[journalist]], [[publisher]] and [[writer]]. She is presently consultant to Penske Business Media LLC and senior editorial contributor for PBM run by media owner Jay Penske.<ref name=\"smith\">{{cite news| url= http://pagesix.com/2017/02/01/nikki-finke-back-in-business-with-jay-penske/ |title= Nikki Finke back in business with Jay Penske  |publisher= New York Post|date=February 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/nikki-finke-94985078 |title=Nikki Finke - Consultant, Penske Business Media, LLC - Penske Media Corporation |website=LinkedIn |access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref> She also is founder and CEO of Hollywood Dementia LLC and its website HollywoodDementia.com for showbiz short fiction.<ref name=NYT>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/30/business/media/feared-hollywood-reporter-turns-to-fiction.html?_r=0/ | work=The New York Times|title=Feared Hollywood Reporter Turns To Fiction|date=May 30, 2015}}</ref> She was the founder, [[editor in chief|editor-in-chief]], and president of ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'', a [[website]] with original content consisting of her and other veteran showbiz journalists' reporting and [[Pundit (expert)|commentary]] on the business of the [[entertainment industry]]. The website was formerly known as Deadline Hollywood Daily. In December 2011, she was given the additional title of editorial advisor of parent company [[Penske Media Corporation|Penske Media Corp]]. Finke has been called the \"most feared, despised, and uncompromising journalist in Hollywood.\"<ref name=\"berrin\">{{cite web |last= Berrin |first= Danielle |url= http://www.jewishjournal.com/hollywoodjew/item/nikki_finke_sells_deadline_hollywood_for_14_million_20090624/ |title= Nikki Finke sells \u2018DeadlineHollywoodDaily.com\u2019 website for $14 million |publisher= The Jewish Journal |location= Greater Los Angeles |date= June 24, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nFinke was born to a [[American Jews|Jewish]] family<ref>[http://www.elle.com/culture/movies-tv/a9158/dkny-model-training-nyfw-dupe3/ Elle Magazine: \"THE GOOD, THE BAD, AND THE UGLY - Out West, where movies and moguls are made, she's the sheriff\" BY LISA CHASE] October 10, 2007 | ''\"Actually, being a woman and being Jewish helps. It's one of the great jokes out here that gentiles are handicapped when it comes to Hollywood.\"''</ref> and raised in [[New York City]], where she attended the Hewitt School,and graduated from [[Wellesley College]],<ref name=\"shanahan2010\">Mark Shanahan & Meredith Goldstein (February 25, 2010). [http://www.boston.com/ae/celebrity/articles/2010/02/25/rapping_it_up/ Rapping it up: Matt keeps going.] ''[[Boston Globe]]''</ref> where she was the editor-in-chief of the school newspaper.{{r|walker20130118}}\n\n==Career==\nFinke's first job after Wellesley was in New York congressman [[Ed Koch]]'s [[Washington, D.C.]] office. According to Finke, she decided to become a reporter after seeing how Koch and his staff \"would genuflect to journalists\". Finke joined the [[Associated Press]] (AP) and covered Koch's successful [[New York City mayoral election, 1977|1977 New York City mayoral campaign]], and worked on the AP's foreign desk at the New York City headquarters,<ref name=\"walker20130118\">{{cite news | url=http://politicker.com/2013/01/how-ed-koch-helped-make-nikki-finke-a-reporter/ | title=How Ed Koch Helped Make Nikki Finke a Reporter | work=New York Observer | date=January 18, 2013 | accessdate=January 19, 2013 | author=Walker, Hunter}}</ref> Baltimore, Boston, Moscow, and London. Finke later worked for ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]''. She joined the staff of ''[[Newsweek]]'' as a correspondent in Washington and Los Angeles, then at the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' as a staff writer covering entertainment and features. Finke became West Coast Editor for ''[[The New York Observer]]'' and then ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'', where she penned Hollywood business columns.  Finke has also written for ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]'', ''[[ELLE|Elle]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[Salon.com]]'', ''[[Premiere (magazine)|Premiere]]'', and ''[[Los Angeles (magazine)|Los Angeles]]'' magazine.\n\nFinke wrote her ''[[LA Weekly]]'' column \"Deadline Hollywood\" from June 2002 to June 2009, and began the ''Deadline'' (''Deadline Hollywood Daily'' until September 2009) blog in March 2006 as a daily online version of her weekly column. She describes it as her \"forum to break news about the [[infotainment]] industry.\"\n\n''The New York Times'' described Finke as \"a digital-age [[Walter Winchell]]\" with an \"in your face\"<ref name=\"friedman\">Friedman, Jon (June 28, 2006). [http://www.marketwatch.com/News/Story/Story.aspx?guid={3FDD7DE6-378C-4E37-974E-04E903B4BA10} In-your-face Finke keeps Hollywood honest.] [[MarketWatch]]</ref> writing style, who is \"feared by [Hollywood] executives\".<ref name=\"carr20090716\">Carr, David. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/17/business/media/17blog.html A Hollywood Blogger Feared by Executives]\" ''The New York Times'', July 17, 2009.</ref> ''Deadline'' became a key information portal during the [[2007 Writers Guild of America strike]], tripling her readership;<ref name=\"stetler\">Stetler, Brian (November 26, 2007). [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/26/business/media/26variety.html Alternative Journalist\u2019s Web Site Is Scrutinized for Writers\u2019 Strike News.] ''[[New York Times]]''</ref><ref name=\"fixmer\">Fixmer, Andy and Michael Janofsky (November 26, 2007). [https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=aqDlk_JfMeBk&refer=us 'Toldja': Nikki Finke Has the Scoop on Hollywood Writers Strike.] Bloomberg.com</ref> according to the ''Times'', \"Finke\u2019s Web site has become a critical forum for Hollywood...But it [is the] strike that may have finally solidified her position as a Hollywood power broker\".<ref name=\"stetler\"/> Finke claimed to have worked \"almost around the clock\" during the strike; in 2009 the ''Los Angeles Times'' noted her announcement of a five-day vacation.<ref name=\"rainey20090715\">Rainey, James. \"[http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jul/15/entertainment/et-onthemedia15 Being relentless and harsh pays off for Deadline Hollywood Daily's Nikki Finke]\" ''Los Angeles Times'', July 15, 2009.</ref>\n\nIn 2008 Finke was named on ''Elle'' magazine's 25 most influential women in Hollywood list,<ref name=\"elle2008\">Staff report (November 2008). 25 most influential women in Hollywood/ ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]''</ref> and to the ''[[Heeb Magazine]]'' 100.<ref name=\"heeb2008\">Staff report (October 2008). [http://www.heebmagazine.com/100 Heeb 100.] ''[[Heeb Magazine]]''</ref> In 2009 she sold ''Deadline'' to [[Jay Penske]]'s Mail.com Media Corp, reportedly for $14 million,<ref name=\"friend20091012\"/> under an agreement by which she would continue as the editor-in-chief and President of the website which would feature her reporting and commentary.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Los Angeles Times|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-ct-deadline24-2009jun24,0,3372246.story|date=June 24, 2009|author=Ben Fritz|title=Nikki Finke's Deadline Hollywood Daily is sold to Mail.com}}</ref>\n\nOn November 5, 2013, Deadline Hollywood announced Nikki Finke's departure.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.deadline.com/2013/11/deadline-com-and-nikki-finke-parting-ways/ |publisher= Deadline |archive-date= 2014 |archive-url= https://www.yahoo.com/tv/news/deadline-com-nikki-finke-parting-ways-022627893.html |title= Deadline.com And Nikki Finke Parting Ways |first1= Mike |last1= Fleming jr |first2= Nellie |last2= Andreeva |date= November 5, 2013 }}</ref> On June 12, 2014, she launched NikkiFinke.com.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nikkifinke.com/first-nikki-post/ |title=First Post |publisher=Nikki Finke |date=June 12, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140817060658/http://nikkifinke.com/first-nikki-post/ |archivedate=August 17, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.buzzfeed.com/kateaurthur/no-one-really-wants-a-nikki-finke-comeback |title= No One Really Wants a Nikki Finke Comeback (Except Nikki Finke) |date= May 29, 2014 |first= Kate |last= Aurthur |publisher= Buzzfeed }}</ref> On August 3, 2015, she launched HollywoodDementia.com<ref name=NYT/> as a site for showbiz short fiction written by her and other insiders. The New York Times said, \"Ms. Finke finds herself facing a daunting new chapter in her career: a plan to leave journalism and write and publish fiction about the entertainment industry.\"\"There is a lot of truth in fiction,\" she said. \"There are things I am going to be able to say in fiction that I can\u2019t say in journalism right now.\" Patrick Goldstein, a former Los Angeles Times film industry columnist told The New York Times that \"everyone [in Hollywood] is secretly full of trepidation about what Nikki\u2019s new site will be like. Will it be literary short stories, or will it be fiction as a thin disguise for the truth?\"<ref name=NYT/>\n\nOn May 11, 2016, Deadline printed Finke's remembrance at how she founded Deadline Hollywood on the occasion of the website's 10-year anniversary. \"When I started Deadline Hollywood Daily, as it was called way back in 2006, I needed a quicker way to report breaking entertainment news than my weekly newspaper column. So I bought the URL DeadlineHollywoodDaily.com for 14 bucks and change. I didn\u2019t set out to be a disruptor. Or an internet journalist who created something out of nothing that put the Hollywood trades back on their heels, and today, under Penske Media ownership, is a website worth $100+ million. Or a woman with brass balls, attitude and ruthless hustle, who told hard truths about the moguls and who accurately reported scoops first.\"<ref name=\"finke\">{{cite web |last= Finke |first= Nikki |url= http://deadline.com/2016/05/nikki-finke-deadline-hollywood-10th-anniversary-1201750730/ |title= Deadline Turns 10: Nikki Finke Looks Back |publisher= Deadline |location= Greater Los Angeles |date= May 11, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nOn February 1, 2017, Finke rejoined Penske's media company.<ref name=\"smith\"/>{{better source|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Praise===\nIn 2006, Finke's ''LA Weekly'' columns won First Place in the Alternative Weekly Awards for the category Media Reporting/Criticism, Circulation >50,000.<ref name=\"aaw2006\">[http://aan.org/alternative/Aan/AwardsView?awardCategory=Media%20Reporting/ Finke's 'Deadline Hollywood' columns in ''LA Weekly'' win 2006 Alt-Weekly Award].\n</ref> In 2007, Finke won the Los Angeles Press Club's Southern California Journalism Award for \"Entertainment Journalist of the Year\" with the judges commenting: \"Reading Nikki Finke\u2019s salaciously candid coverage of Hollywood and its inhabitants almost feels like a guilty pleasure. She mixes the news with fearless finger-wagging that\u2019s just fun to read no matter the subject. She tackles the industry monoliths without the kiddy gloves and she seems to have command of the [[Beat reporting|beat]].\"<ref name=\"lapressclubaward\">[http://lapressclub.org/index.cfm?page=page&pageid=54&cat=45&subcat=54&subsubcat=&id=16406 Southern California Journalism Awards]</ref> In the 2007 AltWeekly Awards, ''Deadline'' won Second Place.<ref name=\"aaw2007\">[http://aan.org/alternative/Aan/ViewArticle?oid=oid%3A187877 Altweekly Awards 2007] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080620053312/http://aan.org/alternative/Aan/ViewArticle?oid=oid%3A187877 |date=June 20, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nA studio executive said of Finke, \"She's very, very, very, accurate, extraordinarily so&mdash;you have a supposedly private conversation with two other people, and it's on her site within an hour.\" Charlie Koones, former ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' publisher, called her a \"once-in-a-generation talent\".<ref name=\"friend20091012\">[[Tad Friend|Friend, Tad]]. \"[http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2009/10/12/091012fa_fact_friend Call Me: Why Hollywood fears Nikki Finke.]\" ''[[The New Yorker]]'', October 12, 2009.</ref>\n\n===Criticism===\nObservers have questioned Finke's \"harsh tone\", \"summary executions\",<ref name=\"rainey20090715\"/> \"penchant for innuendo and unnamed [[Source (journalism)|sources]]\", and allegedly giving better coverage to \"her favorites\"<ref name=\"carr20090716\"/> and frequent sources, such as [[Ari Emanuel]] and [[Ronald Meyer]].<ref name=\"friend20091012\"/> In 2008 she was criticized for first posting a Sony press release and then adding her own analysis which contradicted the release without updating the time stamp, and in early 2009 Finke was accused of retroactively altering<ref name=\"carr20090716\"/><ref name=\"rainey20090715\"/><ref name=\"friend20091012\"/> a ''Deadline Hollywood Daily'' report about the director of the [[Eclipse (2010 film)|third ''Twilight'' film]].<ref name=\"goldstein20090312\">Goldstein, Patrick. \"[http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/the_big_picture/2009/03/that-story-you.html Summit hires new 'Twilight' director, right? Wrong!]\" ''Los Angeles Times'', March 12, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFinke had a 14-year relationship with [[Jeffrey W. Greenberg]], getting engaged in 1974 and married in 1980.<ref name=\"nytengage\"/> They divorced in 1982.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/14/business/yourmoney/divorce-corporate-american-style.html |title=Divorce, Corporate American Style |work=[[New York Times]] |last=Fabrikant |first=Geraldine |date=August 14, 2005 |accessdate=June 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Film criticism]]\n* [[Ezine|E-zines]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Twitter}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.deadline.com/ |title= Deadline |publisher= [[Penske Media Corporation|PMC]] }}\n* Articles\n** {{cite web |url= http://nymag.com/nymag/author_310/ |title= Nikki Finke |publisher= [[New York (magazine)|New York]] }}\n** {{cite web |url= http://www.laweekly.com/authors/nikki-finke-2126818 |title= Nikki Finke |publisher= [[LA Weekly]] }}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Finke, Nikki}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n[[Category:American women journalists]]\n[[Category:American women bloggers]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American journalists]]\n[[Category:Wellesley College alumni]]\n[[Category:Journalists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Women columnists]]\n[[Category:American publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:American women chief executives]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Nikki Finke\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Nikki Finke<ref name=\"nytengage\">Staff report (October 20, 1974). [https://www.nytimes.com/1974/10/20/archives/law-student-fiance-of-nikki-finke.html Law Student Fiance of Nikki Finke.] ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref>\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1953|12}}\n| birth_place   = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| occupation    = [[Writer]], [[journalist]], [[blog]]ger, [[publisher]]\n| spouse=[[Jeffrey W. Greenberg]] (1980\u20131982)\n}}\n\n'''Nikki Finke''' (born 1953) is an American [[blog]]ger,[[journalist]], [[publisher]] and [[writer]]. She is presently consultant to Penske Business Media LLC and senior editorial contributor for PBM run by media owner Jay Penske.<ref name=\"smith\">{{cite news| url= http://pagesix.com/2017/02/01/nikki-finke-back-in-business-with-jay-penske/ |title= Nikki Finke back in business with Jay Penske  |publisher= New York Post|date=February 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/nikki-finke-94985078 |title=Nikki Finke - Consultant, Penske Business Media, LLC - Penske Media Corporation |website=LinkedIn |access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref> She also is founder and CEO of Hollywood Dementia LLC and its website HollywoodDementia.com for showbiz short fiction.<ref name=NYT>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/30/business/media/feared-hollywood-reporter-turns-to-fiction.html?_r=0/ | work=The New York Times|title=Feared Hollywood Reporter Turns To Fiction|date=May 30, 2015}}</ref> She was the founder, [[editor in chief|editor-in-chief]], and president of ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'', a [[website]] with original content consisting of her and other veteran showbiz journalists' reporting and [[Pundit (expert)|commentary]] on the business of the [[entertainment industry]]. The website was formerly known as Deadline Hollywood Daily. In December 2011, she was given the additional title of editorial advisor of parent company [[Penske Media Corporation|Penske Media Corp]]. Finke has been called the \"most feared, despised, and uncompromising journalist in Hollywood.\"<ref name=\"berrin\">{{cite web |last= Berrin |first= Danielle |url= http://www.jewishjournal.com/hollywoodjew/item/nikki_finke_sells_deadline_hollywood_for_14_million_20090624/ |title= Nikki Finke sells \u2018DeadlineHollywoodDaily.com\u2019 website for $14 million |publisher= The Jewish Journal |location= Greater Los Angeles |date= June 24, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nFinke was born to a [[American Jews|Jewish]] family<ref>[http://www.elle.com/culture/movies-tv/a9158/dkny-model-training-nyfw-dupe3/ Elle Magazine: \"THE GOOD, THE BAD, AND THE UGLY - Out West, where movies and moguls are made, she's the sheriff\" BY LISA CHASE] October 10, 2007 | ''\"Actually, being a woman and being Jewish helps. It's one of the great jokes out here that gentiles are handicapped when it comes to Hollywood.\"''</ref> and raised in [[New York City]], where she attended the Hewitt School,and graduated from [[Wellesley College]],<ref name=\"shanahan2010\">Mark Shanahan & Meredith Goldstein (February 25, 2010). [http://www.boston.com/ae/celebrity/articles/2010/02/25/rapping_it_up/ Rapping it up: Matt keeps going.] ''[[Boston Globe]]''</ref> where she was the editor-in-chief of the school newspaper.{{r|walker20130118}}\n\n==Career==\nFinke's first job after Wellesley was in New York congressman [[Ed Koch]]'s [[Washington, D.C.]] office. According to Finke, she decided to become a reporter after seeing how Koch and his staff \"would genuflect to journalists\". Finke joined the [[Associated Press]] (AP) and covered Koch's successful [[New York City mayoral election, 1977|1977 New York City mayoral campaign]], and worked on the AP's foreign desk at the New York City headquarters,<ref name=\"walker20130118\">{{cite news | url=http://politicker.com/2013/01/how-ed-koch-helped-make-nikki-finke-a-reporter/ | title=How Ed Koch Helped Make Nikki Finke a Reporter | work=New York Observer | date=January 18, 2013 | accessdate=January 19, 2013 | author=Walker, Hunter}}</ref> Baltimore, Boston, Moscow, and London. Finke later worked for ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]''. She joined the staff of ''[[Newsweek]]'' as a correspondent in Washington and Los Angeles, then at the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' as a staff writer covering entertainment and features. Finke became West Coast Editor for ''[[The New York Observer]]'' and then ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'', where she penned Hollywood business columns.  Finke has also written for ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]'', ''[[ELLE|Elle]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[Salon.com]]'', ''[[Premiere (magazine)|Premiere]]'', and ''[[Los Angeles (magazine)|Los Angeles]]'' magazine.\n\nFinke wrote her ''[[LA Weekly]]'' column \"Deadline Hollywood\" from June 2002 to June 2009, and began the ''Deadline'' (''Deadline Hollywood Daily'' until September 2009) blog in March 2006 as a daily online version of her weekly column. She describes it as her \"forum to break news about the [[infotainment]] industry.\"\n\n''The New York Times'' described Finke as \"a digital-age [[Walter Winchell]]\" with an \"in your face\"<ref name=\"friedman\">Friedman, Jon (June 28, 2006). [http://www.marketwatch.com/News/Story/Story.aspx?guid={3FDD7DE6-378C-4E37-974E-04E903B4BA10} In-your-face Finke keeps Hollywood honest.] [[MarketWatch]]</ref> writing style, who is \"feared by [Hollywood] executives\".<ref name=\"carr20090716\">Carr, David. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/17/business/media/17blog.html A Hollywood Blogger Feared by Executives]\" ''The New York Times'', July 17, 2009.</ref> ''Deadline'' became a key information portal during the [[2007 Writers Guild of America strike]], tripling her readership;<ref name=\"stetler\">Stetler, Brian (November 26, 2007). [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/26/business/media/26variety.html Alternative Journalist\u2019s Web Site Is Scrutinized for Writers\u2019 Strike News.] ''[[New York Times]]''</ref><ref name=\"fixmer\">Fixmer, Andy and Michael Janofsky (November 26, 2007). [https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=aqDlk_JfMeBk&refer=us 'Toldja': Nikki Finke Has the Scoop on Hollywood Writers Strike.] Bloomberg.com</ref> according to the ''Times'', \"Finke\u2019s Web site has become a critical forum for Hollywood...But it [is the] strike that may have finally solidified her position as a Hollywood power broker\".<ref name=\"stetler\"/> Finke claimed to have worked \"almost around the clock\" during the strike; in 2009 the ''Los Angeles Times'' noted her announcement of a five-day vacation.<ref name=\"rainey20090715\">Rainey, James. \"[http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jul/15/entertainment/et-onthemedia15 Being relentless and harsh pays off for Deadline Hollywood Daily's Nikki Finke]\" ''Los Angeles Times'', July 15, 2009.</ref>\n\nIn 2008 Finke was named on ''Elle'' magazine's 25 most influential women in Hollywood list,<ref name=\"elle2008\">Staff report (November 2008). 25 most influential women in Hollywood/ ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]''</ref> and to the ''[[Heeb Magazine]]'' 100.<ref name=\"heeb2008\">Staff report (October 2008). [http://www.heebmagazine.com/100 Heeb 100.] ''[[Heeb Magazine]]''</ref> In 2009 she sold ''Deadline'' to [[Jay Penske]]'s Mail.com Media Corp, reportedly for $14 million,<ref name=\"friend20091012\"/> under an agreement by which she would continue as the editor-in-chief and President of the website which would feature her reporting and commentary.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Los Angeles Times|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-ct-deadline24-2009jun24,0,3372246.story|date=June 24, 2009|author=Ben Fritz|title=Nikki Finke's Deadline Hollywood Daily is sold to Mail.com}}</ref>\n\nOn November 5, 2013, Deadline Hollywood announced Nikki Finke's departure.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.deadline.com/2013/11/deadline-com-and-nikki-finke-parting-ways/ |publisher= Deadline |archive-date= 2014 |archive-url= https://www.yahoo.com/tv/news/deadline-com-nikki-finke-parting-ways-022627893.html |title= Deadline.com And Nikki Finke Parting Ways |first1= Mike |last1= Fleming jr |first2= Nellie |last2= Andreeva |date= November 5, 2013 }}</ref> On June 12, 2014, she launched NikkiFinke.com.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nikkifinke.com/first-nikki-post/ |title=First Post |publisher=Nikki Finke |date=June 12, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140817060658/http://nikkifinke.com/first-nikki-post/ |archivedate=August 17, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.buzzfeed.com/kateaurthur/no-one-really-wants-a-nikki-finke-comeback |title= No One Really Wants a Nikki Finke Comeback (Except Nikki Finke) |date= May 29, 2014 |first= Kate |last= Aurthur |publisher= Buzzfeed }}</ref> On August 3, 2015, she launched HollywoodDementia.com<ref name=NYT/> as a site for showbiz short fiction written by her and other insiders. The New York Times said, \"Ms. Finke finds herself facing a daunting new chapter in her career: a plan to leave journalism and write and publish fiction about the entertainment industry.\"\"There is a lot of truth in fiction,\" she said. \"There are things I am going to be able to say in fiction that I can\u2019t say in journalism right now.\" Patrick Goldstein, a former Los Angeles Times film industry columnist told The New York Times that \"everyone [in Hollywood] is secretly full of trepidation about what Nikki\u2019s new site will be like. Will it be literary short stories, or will it be fiction as a thin disguise for the truth?\"<ref name=NYT/>\n\nOn May 11, 2016, Deadline printed Finke's remembrance at how she founded Deadline Hollywood on the occasion of the website's 10-year anniversary. \"When I started Deadline Hollywood Daily, as it was called way back in 2006, I needed a quicker way to report breaking entertainment news than my weekly newspaper column. So I bought the URL DeadlineHollywoodDaily.com for 14 bucks and change. I didn\u2019t set out to be a disruptor. Or an internet journalist who created something out of nothing that put the Hollywood trades back on their heels, and today, under Penske Media ownership, is a website worth $100+ million. Or a woman with brass balls, attitude and ruthless hustle, who told hard truths about the moguls and who accurately reported scoops first.\"<ref name=\"finke\">{{cite web |last= Finke |first= Nikki |url= http://deadline.com/2016/05/nikki-finke-deadline-hollywood-10th-anniversary-1201750730/ |title= Deadline Turns 10: Nikki Finke Looks Back |publisher= Deadline |location= Greater Los Angeles |date= May 11, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nOn February 1, 2017, Finke rejoined Penske's media company.<ref name=\"smith\"/>{{better source|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Praise===\nIn 2006, Finke's ''LA Weekly'' columns won First Place in the Alternative Weekly Awards for the category Media Reporting/Criticism, Circulation >50,000.<ref name=\"aaw2006\">[http://aan.org/alternative/Aan/AwardsView?awardCategory=Media%20Reporting/ Finke's 'Deadline Hollywood' columns in ''LA Weekly'' win 2006 Alt-Weekly Award].\n</ref> In 2007, Finke won the Los Angeles Press Club's Southern California Journalism Award for \"Entertainment Journalist of the Year\" with the judges commenting: \"Reading Nikki Finke\u2019s salaciously candid coverage of Hollywood and its inhabitants almost feels like a guilty pleasure. She mixes the news with fearless finger-wagging that\u2019s just fun to read no matter the subject. She tackles the industry monoliths without the kiddy gloves and she seems to have command of the [[Beat reporting|beat]].\"<ref name=\"lapressclubaward\">[http://lapressclub.org/index.cfm?page=page&pageid=54&cat=45&subcat=54&subsubcat=&id=16406 Southern California Journalism Awards]</ref> In the 2007 AltWeekly Awards, ''Deadline'' won Second Place.<ref name=\"aaw2007\">[http://aan.org/alternative/Aan/ViewArticle?oid=oid%3A187877 Altweekly Awards 2007] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080620053312/http://aan.org/alternative/Aan/ViewArticle?oid=oid%3A187877 |date=June 20, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nA studio executive said of Finke, \"She's very, very, very, accurate, extraordinarily so&mdash;you have a supposedly private conversation with two other people, and it's on her site within an hour.\" Charlie Koones, former ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' publisher, called her a \"once-in-a-generation talent\".<ref name=\"friend20091012\">[[Tad Friend|Friend, Tad]]. \"[http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2009/10/12/091012fa_fact_friend Call Me: Why Hollywood fears Nikki Finke.]\" ''[[The New Yorker]]'', October 12, 2009.</ref>\n\n===Criticism===\nObservers have questioned Finke's \"harsh tone\", \"summary executions\",<ref name=\"rainey20090715\"/> \"penchant for innuendo and unnamed [[Source (journalism)|sources]]\", and allegedly giving better coverage to \"her favorites\"<ref name=\"carr20090716\"/> and frequent sources, such as [[Ari Emanuel]] and [[Ronald Meyer]].<ref name=\"friend20091012\"/> In 2008 she was criticized for first posting a Sony press release and then adding her own analysis which contradicted the release without updating the time stamp, and in early 2009 Finke was accused of retroactively altering<ref name=\"carr20090716\"/><ref name=\"rainey20090715\"/><ref name=\"friend20091012\"/> a ''Deadline Hollywood Daily'' report about the director of the [[Eclipse (2010 film)|third ''Twilight'' film]].<ref name=\"goldstein20090312\">Goldstein, Patrick. \"[http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/the_big_picture/2009/03/that-story-you.html Summit hires new 'Twilight' director, right? Wrong!]\" ''Los Angeles Times'', March 12, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFinke had a 14-year relationship with [[Jeffrey W. Greenberg]], getting engaged in 1974 and married in 1980.<ref name=\"nytengage\"/> They divorced in 1982.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/14/business/yourmoney/divorce-corporate-american-style.html |title=Divorce, Corporate American Style |work=[[New York Times]] |last=Fabrikant |first=Geraldine |date=August 14, 2005 |accessdate=June 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Film criticism]]\n* [[Ezine|E-zines]]\n\n==References==\n{{refli